[11] Brazil (ex USA/FL)
Date: 21 Jan 2013
Source: Centre for Epidemiological Surveillance/SES/SP [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.JW, edited]
http://www.cve.saude.sp.gov.br/htm/resp/pdf/alerta_sarampo_21jan13.pdf


The State of Sao Paulo (SP) has had no endemic circulation of measles virus since 2000. However, in 2011, there were 27 measles cases, with 18 of them occurring as 2 outbreaks in schools. The 1st cases in 2011 occurred in late January 2011 with a history of travel to Florida, USA. Most cases (n=23) in SP occurred between August and December 2011, with the last case exhibiting the characteristic rash on 25 Dec 2011. There was no record of any confirmed cases of measles in SP during 2012.

On Wed 2 Jan 2013, a suspected case of measles in a 20-year-old resident of the city of Bauru (SP state) with a history of international travel to Florida, USA in December 2012 tested positive for measles virus genotype D8 by RT-PCR and sequencing performed at Fiocruzon on the initial sample (2 Jan 2013). Measles virus genotype D8 is circulating in England and has been detected in other countries, including the USA, Canada and China. On Wed 9 Jan 2013, a traveler living in Minas Gerais, who returned on the same flight, presented with rash and fever. On Thu 10 Jan 2013, 2 family contacts who had accompanied the 1st case also became symptomatic. All cases are under investigation until the final diagnosis.

Sao Paulo state is characterised by heavy daily international, interstate and intrastate traffic. In a few weeks will begin the return from summer vacation and the start of classes. Thus, it is important that everyone keep their vaccination status updated according to the state immunization schedule, especially professionals in the health sector, education and tourism.

Vaccination coverage in the State of Sao Paulo for measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccination in 2012 (provisional data up to 19 Dec 2012) is 99.8 percent (68 percent homogeneity). Vaccination coverage in GVE XV Bauru is 104 percent (71 percent homogeneity). Vaccination coverage in Bauru is 111 percent [Reported vaccination coverages of over 100 percent are explained by either underestimates of the denominator (population estimates), or vaccination of more individuals than should have been, either people coming from outside of the vaccination centers catchment area or vaccinating outside of the recommended age range, or mismanagement of records. According to Teixeira and Rocha, homogeneity of vaccination coverages is defined as the proportion of municipalities with vaccination coverages equal or greater than 95 percent (see Teixeira AMS, Rocha CMV. Vigilancia das coberturas de vacinacao: uma metodologia para deteccao e intervencao em situacoes de risco. Epidemiologia e Servicos de Saude 2010;19(3):217-226. available at: http://portal.saude.gov.br/portal/arquivos/pdf/vigilancia_coberturas_vacinais_antonia.pdf in Portuguese). - Mod.MPP].

The CV Rubella Vaccination Campaign that was held in 2008 for people between 20 and 39 years of age in SP state was 94.6 percent (56 percent homogeneity) and for GVE in Bauru was 87.5 percent (homogeneity 50 percent). In the city of Bauru, it was 79 percent.

The 1st dose of MMR vaccine is applied at 12 months with a 2nd dose between 4 and 6 years old. Importantly, the 1st dose applied at 12 months old is considered sufficient. A 2nd dose is recommended for people 19 years of age. For unvaccinated adults, the MMR vaccine is recommended for those born after 1960.

