[12] USA (OR)
Date: Thu 24 Jan 2013
Source: Katu.com [edited]
http://www.katu.com/news/local/Case-of-measles-reported-in-Marion-County-188290191.html


A case of measles, a highly contagious and rare illness, has been reported out of Marion County.

Public health officials reported that someone who had traveled internationally started to exhibit symptoms and was diagnosed on Wednesday [23 Jan 2013] at Doernbecher Children's Hospital. The person has been infectious since 18 Jan 2013, officials said.

Health experts say more than 95 percent of people living in the Pacific Northwest have been vaccinated and are immune to measles. Still, because measles is a highly contagious respiratory disease and a potentially serious infection, health officials want the public to be on alert for symptoms. Specifically, officials say people who were at the locations below at these times are susceptible to contracting the illness:

- Marshall's store at Keizer Station, 6365 Ulali Dr. N.E., between 2 p.m. and 5 p.m. on 20 Jan 2013.
- Target, 6450 Keizer Station Blvd. N.E., between 3 p.m. and 7 p.m. on 20 Jan 2013.
- Walgreen's, 4380 Commercial St. S.E. in Salem, between 2:30 p.m. and 5 p.m. on 22 Jan 2013.
- OHSU Doernbecher Children's Hospital main lobby and 7th floor clinics, between 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. on 23 Jan 2013.

Folks living in Marion County wishing to get vaccinated for measles should contact their medical provider or the Marion County Health Department at 503-584-4870.

